<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">U-Line is the undercounter ice and cooling specialist — and most of the U-Line calls we run in LA are ice makers in Beverly Hills and Malibu home bars that stopped producing ice or are making small / hollow cubes.</h2>

    <p>U-Line Corporation (Milwaukee, Wisconsin, founded 1962, independent and privately held) built its identity around one product category and stayed there. The US lineup is undercounter ice makers, undercounter refrigerators, wine captains, beverage centers, and outdoor-rated variants of each — that's the entire scope of the brand. No ranges, no dishwashers, no full-size refrigerators, no laundry under the U-Line name. Six decades of engineering focus on one category produces a parts catalog and a service tree that's narrower and deeper than full-line brands. The U-BI95B 15-inch built-in ice maker dominates the indoor side; the U-CO29B outdoor ice maker dominates the outdoor side; together they account for most of our U-Line service volume across the Westside and Malibu coastal strip.</p>

    <p>Two U-Line-specific realities shape every service call we run. First, <strong>clear ice production is a different mechanism than standard cube ice</strong>. U-Line's premium ice makers use a slow-freeze process that lets air bubbles escape before the cube solidifies — the result is the optically clear cocktail-grade ice that's the entire reason these units get specified into Beverly Hills home bars and Malibu pool decks. Practical service implication: clear-ice production runs slower and uses different sensor calibration than commercial flake or cube machines, so the symptom tree on a U-Line ice maker is different from a <a href="/brands/scotsman-ice-machine-repair/">Scotsman</a> or <a href="/brands/hoshizaki-ice-machine-repair/">Hoshizaki</a> commercial unit. Second, <strong>LA hard water is the single largest accelerant of U-Line ice maker failure</strong>. Municipal water across the LA basin carries mineral content that scales the water inlet valve, the fill solenoid, and the small water-line passages inside the ice mold — the 2014-2019 U-BI95 cohort develops a consistent water inlet valve failure pattern around year 5 to 7, and the addresses without inline water filters see it earliest.</p>

    <p>This page covers U-Line repair across the full US lineup. Every U-Line service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM U-Line parts via Milwaukee distribution, and an honest written quote with parts lead-time disclosed before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 ICE MAKERS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, U-Line ice makers — the core service category</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">U-BI built-in and U-CO outdoor ice makers dominate the U-Line service mix.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Ice maker work accounts for the bulk of our U-Line volume in LA. The U-BI95B (15-inch built-in, clear ice, the indoor flagship) anchors Beverly Hills / Bel Air / Pacific Palisades home bars; the U-CO29B (24-inch outdoor, marine-grade stainless, 110°F ambient rated) anchors Malibu and Newport Coast outdoor kitchens. Both share the same core engineering platform with marine-grade differences on the outdoor variant.</p>

    <div class="callout-box">
      <h3>2014-2019 U-BI95 water inlet valve pattern (most common U-Line service call in LA)</h3>
      <p>The U-BI95B and surrounding U-BI series production years between roughly 2014 and 2019 develop a consistent water inlet valve failure around year 5 to 7. Symptoms: ice maker produces small or hollow cubes (mold underfills), eventually stops producing ice entirely, sometimes a hissing or whining sound when the valve tries to open. <strong>LA hard water is the main accelerant</strong> — mineral buildup inside the valve solenoid restricts flow before the part fails outright. Addresses without inline water filters see this fail earliest (year 4-5); filtered installs push it to year 7-9. Replacement runs $185-$285, often same-day when we stock the common U-BI valves on the truck. Worth pairing with a water-line tap inspection at the same visit — the 1/4-inch saddle-valve taps used in most DIY installs clog with the same mineral scale, and a new tap (or a full feed-line replacement on visibly fouled lines) extends the new valve's service life.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond the water inlet valve pattern, U-Line ice maker service covers a predictable set of items:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 3-5:</strong> Water-line tap mineral fouling ($145-$245 for tap and short-line replacement), thermostat drift on older non-electronic units ($185-$285).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5-7:</strong> Water inlet valve (above) — the dominant U-Line ice maker service item. Door gasket replacement on heavily-used units ($185-$285).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 6-9:</strong> Drain pump on heated-tray variants ($245-$385) — the pump that removes ice melt from the bin during defrost cycles. Failure produces standing water in the bin and accelerated bin-frost buildup.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 7-10:</strong> Ice maker module assembly ($345-$525) — the integrated fill arm / harvest motor / thermostat unit. Evaporator fan motor ($245-$385) on fan-cooled variants.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8-12:</strong> Condenser fan motor ($285-$425), control board ($345-$525), fill arm or harvest motor isolation when the full module isn't needed.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 10+:</strong> Compressor replacement ($580-$880). Repair-vs-replace math gets closer at this point — U-BI95B replacement is around $3,400, so a compressor swap on a year-12 unit is still repair territory but the calculation tightens.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The clear ice production process is what distinguishes U-Line ice makers from standard cube machines and from commercial ice ecosystem. Slow-freeze from the bottom of the mold up lets dissolved air escape before the cube solidifies — the result is the optically transparent cocktail ice these units get specified for. Service implication: when a U-Line is producing cloudy or partially-clear ice, the issue is almost always upstream water quality (mineral content, dissolved air from a fouled feed line) rather than the slow-freeze mechanism itself. We test water at the inlet during diagnostic when cloudy-ice symptoms come in.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 UNDERCOUNTER, WINE, OUTDOOR -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Undercounter refrigerators, wine captains, beverage centers, outdoor</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The rest of the U-Line lineup.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Beyond ice, U-Line covers undercounter refrigerators (U-UCR series), wine captains (U-WC), beverage centers (U-BEV), and outdoor-rated variants of each. The service trees overlap with the ice maker side on shared components (compressor, condenser fan, control board) but add category-specific items.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Undercounter refrigerators (U-UCR series)</h3>
        <p>U-UCR24 dominates — all-refrigerator and refrigerator/freezer 24-inch undercounter configurations. Service tree: compressor relay year 5-7, evaporator fan year 7-9, door gasket year 4-6. ADA-compliant variants ship with an offset door hinge geometry that requires a different adjustment procedure than the standard configuration — we identify the variant before quoting hinge work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Outdoor ice makers (U-CO series, marine-grade)</h3>
        <p>U-CO29B is the dominant outdoor ice maker in our LA service mix. Marine-grade stainless construction, 110°F ambient rated. Coastal addresses (Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Newport Coast) see accelerated wear on water inlet valve, condenser fan, and electrical terminals — salt aerosol corrodes copper and brass faster than the rated service life assumes. Service items run faster than indoor U-BI equivalents.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Wine captains (U-WC series)</h3>
        <p>U-WC24 single-zone and dual-zone wine units. Service items: thermostat / thermistor drift year 6-8, evaporator fan year 7-9, compressor relay year 5-7. Cross-references to broader wine cooler service — see our <a href="/services/wine-cellar-cooling-repair/">wine cellar cooling service hub</a> for the cross-brand wine-storage coverage including <a href="/brands/sub-zero/">Sub-Zero</a> wine columns and <a href="/brands/u-line-wine-cooler-repair/">U-Line wine cooler</a> details.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Beverage centers (U-BEV series)</h3>
        <p>U-BEV24 glass-front beverage units with fan-forced circulation for fast chilled-drink pull-down. Engineered for chilled beverages rather than long-term wine storage — different temperature profile, different system tuning. Service items: evaporator fan, thermostat, door gasket, control board. Common in West Hollywood condos and Newport Beach home bars.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Outdoor refrigerators (U-CO refrigerator variants)</h3>
        <p>The CO outdoor refrigerator variants pair with the CO outdoor ice makers in custom outdoor kitchens. Marine-grade stainless, 110°F rated. Same coastal-corrosion service profile as the outdoor ice makers. See our <a href="/brands/u-line-outdoor-refrigerator-repair/">U-Line outdoor refrigerator repair</a> page for outdoor-specific service details.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Honest scope — what U-Line doesn't make</h3>
        <p>No full-size refrigerators, ranges, ovens, cooktops, dishwashers, microwaves, washers, or dryers under the U-Line brand. U-Line specializes in undercounter ice and cooling — that's the entire scope. For full-size kitchen appliances, see our <a href="/services/">services hub</a> for the cross-brand coverage by appliance category.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

