    <p class="price-note">Repair-vs-replace math on U-Line runs case-by-case at year 10+. Replacement-unit pricing is $2,800-$4,500 depending on configuration (U-BI95B clear-ice around $3,400 list, U-CO29B outdoor around $4,200, U-UCR24 undercounter around $2,800, U-WC24 wine captain around $3,200). Through year 8-9, repair almost always wins for any quote under $500. At year 10-12 with a $580-$880 compressor swap on a $3,000-class unit, the math gets closer to replacement, especially on entry-tier models. We tell you the math at diagnostic before authorization — U-Line is niche enough that we treat each repair-vs-replace decision as case-by-case rather than rule-driven.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">U-Line jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Three representative service calls — model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; technical scenarios are typical of what we see on U-Line service.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>U-Line U-BI95B built-in ice maker, Beverly Hills home bar</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Ice maker producing small, partially hollow cubes for about 2 weeks, then stopped producing ice entirely 3 days before the call. Owner heard a faint hissing sound when the unit cycled. Unit was 6 years old, on an unfiltered water line.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Classic 2014-2019 U-BI95 water inlet valve failure. Valve solenoid restricted by hard-water mineral buildup — partial flow first (small / hollow cubes), then full failure to open. Water-line tap inspected and found heavily fouled with mineral scale matching the valve symptom.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Water inlet valve replacement with OEM U-Line part (in stock on truck). New 1/4-inch saddle-valve tap and short feed-line section. Verified full mold fill and clear-ice production on a complete cycle. Recommended inline water filter install for future protection.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $325 total (valve + new tap + short line). Same-day, 90 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>U-Line U-CO29B outdoor ice maker, Malibu pool deck</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Outdoor ice maker producing about 40% of normal ice volume, with the bin filling much slower than usual. Owner reported a green-tinged corrosion deposit visible on the back panel where the water line connects. Unit was 5 years old, oceanfront Carbon Beach address.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Water inlet valve corrosion from coastal salt aerosol — the bronze valve body had developed verdigris that restricted flow. Plus the brass water-line fitting at the back of the unit showed matching corrosion. Condenser fan motor measured within spec but coils showed salt-deposit film that warranted cleaning.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Water inlet valve replacement with marine-grade OEM U-Line part. New brass-to-stainless water-line transition fitting at the unit inlet. Condenser coil and electrical terminal cleaning. Verified normal production rate and ice clarity on test cycle.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $445 total (marine-grade valve + fitting + coastal-corrosion cleaning service). Same-day, 2 hours on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>U-Line U-UCR24 undercounter refrigerator, Pacific Palisades</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Undercounter refrigerator running 6-8°F above setpoint for about 10 days. Owner had set to 38°F, unit was holding 44-46°F. No error displayed. Unit was 8 years old, under a wet-bar countertop.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Evaporator fan motor running at reduced RPM — year 8 bearing wear consistent with the standard U-UCR service curve. Airflow over the evaporator dropped enough that the unit couldn't pull down to setpoint reliably. Compressor measured within spec; condenser coils were clean.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Evaporator fan motor replacement with OEM U-Line part. Verified normal temperature pull-down to setpoint over a 6-hour soak. Door gasket inspected and found acceptable (no replacement needed despite the 8-year age).</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $315 total. Same-day, 75 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

